At the beginning of this year, my name was a clue to a crossword puzzle in a major U.S. newspaper. Seventy-Two Across was four letters: “Megan Falley creation.” The answer was ‘poem’, but my brother asked if it was ‘love’. The New Year is one of my high holy holidays. Each December 31st I reflect with earnest intensity, and set my intentions in my most immaculate handwriting. I make my own little resolutions about the habits I want to adopt, the art I want to create. When feeling into the beauty, the growth, the tough and the tender of 2022, and what I want to call-in hereafter, I thought of my brother. His accidental compliment. My want for this year, and all years moving forward, is that when people think of what I’ve created in this life, the answer is love.

i’m often asked about my writing routine—and while i think the best routine is the one that works for YOU, i will say that reading a book for at least twenty minutes before i start writing feels pretty non-negotiable to me if i’m to produce anything good. first, it calms the system and helps settle any anxiety related to writing. second, it operates as a bridge between the outside world and the creative process. third, every book you read teaches you something about writing and the craft of it, especially if you’re paying attention to that part. i keep a separate notebook for my ‘word collection’ - almost all have been found through reading - and when my prose is getting predictable i open it up and throw a new word in there. it’s like literary confetti. so if you’re feeling stuck in your writing, amp up your reading! i’m currently reading “god shot” by the incredible @chelseabieker. what books have inspired you lately? 

PS. swipe to the end to see my treadmill desk. adhd hack to the max.

completely true facts about @oliviagatwood :

1. “hey there delilah” by american rock band ‘plain white t’s’ was originally titled “hey there olivia” and was written for her too, but in a last minute lover’s spat she pulled the legal rites to her own name. no one knows who the fuck delilah is. 

2. once, when she ran out of fake lashes, olivia split a centipede in half and glued it on to her eyelids. it was very punk rock. also the centipede was not harmed and thanked her for the best night of its life. 

3. we met as children on an enclosed water slide at splish splash water park (96 acres of family fun). somehow olivia got stuck in the middle of the tube and i slid down and found her and we just sat there in the dark wet encasement talking for hours while water surged around us until the park shut down. after, we got dip-n-dots. 

4. oh, and today is her birthday. happy birthday olivia. my love for you is one of the truest things about me. ✨

in honor of national poetry month, i want to share a few favorite moments from my debut collection, ‘after the witch hunt.’ this book was published by @writebloodypublishing over a decade ago, and while i hope every writer reflects on their earlier work and can benchmark the growth of both their craft and personhood, it’s pretty rad to look back and see that even though i wrote a lot of these poems when i was 22 or younger––sometimes i got it right.

in 2014, i began writing poems about lana del rey. poems that looked at her, poems that looked at me through her eyes. say what you will about lana, but this was in the top two transformative experiences of my writing life. by embodying her persona, i was better able to see myself. with the angel and devil of her on the shoulders of my consciousness, i made braver, sexier, wilder choices. i lived. sometimes writing feels as if it is the opposite of living — just another way to stare at a screen. but really, my writing is inseparable from my life, and it is through exploring on the page that i have cultivated some of my deepest moments of growth and connection. so here’s some snippets of my chapbook, “bad girls, honey”, as well as snapshots of me dressing up as lana and taking selfies in my underwear. because obviously. happy national poetry month. #lanadelrey #poetry #instapoetry

it is hard to know which anniversary to count as ours. our years have been marked by so many calendar moments, worthy-firsts. is it august 10th, our first dance in that nightclub, whose longitude and latitude i now have tattooed on my arms? or is it when i read a poem for you in public about wanting to hold your hand (april 2nd) or sixteen days later, when i finally did hold it, that fluttering bird? maybe it’s august 13th, your birthday, the first we spent together where i gave you 40 presents, one for every year i missed. or maybe it’s your birthday, but years later, when i got down on one knee and you said yes to my forever. for whatever reason though, it is this day i count the most, may 13th, when i visited you in colorado because you got us tickets to a Lana Del Rey concert at Red Rocks and i woke up christmas-morning excited, checking her site for the details, only to realize the concert was the day before. you thought i’d be so sad, but i spent the evening falling never-look-back in love with you. that was eight years ago today. best concert i never went to. so much music.

happy mother’s day to the woman that will jump out of airplanes with me—figuratively, literally. my parachute. thank you for carrying me for nine months and then for thirty-four years after. and thanks for making my name your instagram handle. i love you, @seanmegan6109 ✨

Yesterday, Andrea was inaugurated as the Poet Laureate of Colorado as selected by Governor Jared Polis. The event was so beautiful, backdropped by Boulder’s mountain range, with a good friend in half the folding chairs. Andrea read two poems. There is nothing more sacred to me than when a writer lassos the wild beast of this existence and manages to keep it still just long enough for the rest of us to see it fully, to go, “Ah, yes, that is exactly it,” before setting the truth free in our hearts. That is Andrea. Poet Laureate, yes, or maybe Literary Cowboy. But someone who always looks at this life in the eye and dares to see the whole of it for us. Congratulations, @andreagibson, and the whole state of Colorado who is so lucky to have you represent them. Anyway pretty sure I’m the first lady.

ELEVEN years ago, I was working at Trader Joe’s, living in my mom’s house, with a BA in English Literature. My first book had just been published, and my boss (or Captain, as they put it in TJ’s lingo) was gracious enough to allow me to take three months off from work to go on a book tour. The tour itself was just me in my old, beat up Altima. It was 40 something shows, 100 days long. I drove over 13,000 miles, and only stayed in a hotel twice––the other times I slept on the futons, couches, guest beds of poets and strangers. In that way, my tour was subsidized on kindness. What I didn’t know would happen would be that I wouldn’t go back to the grocery store again. That I would somehow be both lucky and scrappy enough to make a career as a full-time writer. It wasn’t always glamorous, but there has never been a day where I don’t feel like I won the creative lottery. Poetry has given me so much. As a teacher, I want to give all of it back. My online writing workshop @PoemsThatDontSuck begins again on October 1st. If you want to discover together the gifts that writing might have in store for you, you can snag your tuition at meganfalley.com/shop. 

Anyway, here are some photos of me and the books I’ve written throughout the years, as well as the best things poetry has given me. Swipe to the end for my earliest literary masterpiece.

i haven’t spoken much online about andrea’s diagnosis and what the last two years have been like for me. andrea has been so eloquent that sometimes it felt like there was nothing left to be said. but then glennon and abby invited us on a virtual double date, and as always they created a soft place for the truth to land. 

come listen to the story of how @andreagibson and i fell in love once, and then fell back in love all over again two years ago when we received the news that did not shatter our world, but made kintsugi of it. 

thank you to the entire #wecandohardthings crew & pod squad. also, @glennondoyle & @abbywambach –– will you be our double dates forever? 

#wcdht

we fell in love on a dance floor. when we stopped going out, we turned our home into a dance floor. and there’s nothing we want to dance to more than our friend @jessethomas_____ who makes the smartest, truest, most good-kind-of-contagious pop music. andrea and i feel like this was written about us, for us. but isn’t that what all the best music does? check out jesse’s new song and try not to dance. i dare you.

Since I was nine years old, I have struggled with my body size, body image, and other patriarchal and capitalistic pressures of beauty. When my partner was diagnosed with cancer over two years ago, I was overcome with the futility of hating my healthy body. I am so grateful to Ned Buskirik at @YerGoing2Die for inviting me onto his trailblazing podcast to talk about the intersection of body image and mortality. And thank you to @AndreaGibson, as always, for shaking up the kaleidoscope of my life toward a more beautiful picture. You can hear the whole conversation at the link in my bio.

these photos are all taken within 3 minutes of my home. but before you get too jealous of the colorado landscape, let me inform you that in the last two months, there have been not one, but TWO snakes inside of my house. separate instances. and one was a four footer in my laundry room. i have literally not been the same since. anyway enjoy the pretty pictures.

Megan Falley @meganfalley 
talking about the impact of her partner poet Andrea Gibson’s @andreagibson cancer diagnosis on You're Going to Die: The Podcast…

Join host Ned Buskirk in conversation with queer femme writer, spoken word poet, author, & teaching artist Megan Falley, while they talk about how two decades of hating her body shifted with her partner’s cancer diagnosis, how confronting mortality altered her idea of what beauty is, & how being a steward over her partner’s health lead to a decision to vow some of that same love & devotion to herself.

it’s been a wild couple months. i spent much of it in bed super sick watching “sex education” and also finding out that i may have magical powers. if you’re looking to read a nonfiction fairytale, check out andrea’s free newsletter on substack this week. [andreagibson.substack.com] ✨ ⚡️ 💛

friends, i think i could comfortably sit and talk with @glennondoyle for the rest of my life. she is one of the smartest, funniest, wisest and most generous people i’ve had the lucky stars to know. i am so grateful for our one-on-one conversation on the ‘we can do hard things’ podcast [of which i am a total podsquatter] where we discussed all my favorite topics: bodies, queerness, nuance!!!!, forgiveness and love. listen @ link in bio or wherever you get your podcasts! ✨

like so many across the globe, i often listen to ‘we can do hard things’ in the morning while getting ready for my day, pretending i am in a warm room of wise friends, feeling fed. a good podcast can feel like a coffee date, or church, or a classroom, or therapy. i am so touched to be on the other side of that alchemy today as the pod-squad and beyond listen in on a conversation between me and the inimitable @glennondoyle. i hope you check out the episode and, like me, feel a little less lonely, a little more open, more held, more brave. 💗
